<h2><a name='sect0' href='#toc0'>Name</a></h2>
<b>MPI_T_pvar_read</b> - Read the value of a performance variable
<h2><a name='sect1' href='#toc1'>Syntax</a></h2>

<h2><a name='sect2' href='#toc2'>C Syntax</a></h2>
<br>
<pre>#include &lt;mpi.h&gt;
int MPI_T_pvar_read(MPI_T_pvar_session session, MPI_T_pvar_handle handle,
const void *buf)
</pre>
<h2><a name='sect3' href='#toc3'>Input Parameters</a></h2>

<dl>

<dt>session </dt>
<dd>Performance experiment session. </dd>

<dt>handle </dt>
<dd>Performance
variable handle. </dd>

<dt>buf </dt>
<dd>Initial address of storage location for variable value.

<p> </dd>
</dl>

<h2><a name='sect4' href='#toc4'>Description</a></h2>
MPI_T_pvar_read queries the value of a performance variable
identified by the handle specified in <i>handle</i> in the session specified in
<i>session</i>. The result is stored in the buffer pointed to by <i>buf</i>. The caller
must ensure that the buffer pointed to by <i>buf</i> is large enough to hold the
entire value of the performance variable.
<p>
<h2><a name='sect5' href='#toc5'>Errors</a></h2>
MPI_T_pvar_read() will
fail if:
<dl>

<dt>[MPI_T_ERR_NOT_INITIALIZED] </dt>
<dd>The MPI Tools interface not initialized
</dd>

<dt>[MPI_T_ERR_INVALID_HANDLE] </dt>
<dd>The handle is invalid or not associated with
the session </dd>

<dt>[MPI_T_ERR_INVALID_SESSION] </dt>
<dd>Session argument is not a valid

<p>session
<p> </dd>
</dl>

